    "sourceTitle1": "Ministry of Culture - Study on the Monuments of the Ottoman Period in Thessaloniki.",
    "description": `Bezesteni is an Ottoman monument built on Sultan Mehmet II Era (1455-1459). It is located in Thessaloniki at the intersection of Venizelos and Solomou streets, opposite the Hamza Bey Mosque and the old town hall of the city. The word is worded by the Turkish word bezesten, which means an ancient shop and comes from the Arabic word bez meaning fabric.
    </br></br>The architecture style is representative of the Ottoman architecture in the 15th century and is also found in other similar buildings in Serres and in the Balkan area. Bezesteni was a very important institution of Ottoman cities. There, valuable items were sold, documents and assets were kept, commodity quality was controlled, and exchange rates were determined.

    </br></br>It is a rectangular space with an entrance on each of its four sides. Inside it is divided into six quadrilateral spaces with seven double arcs resting on two central pillars. The building has six lead-made domes. Prior to the fire in 1917, which destroyed most of the city center, Bezesteni numbered 113 stores in total. After the fire around the central area, external stores were added.

    </br></br>In the 1980s and 1990s, restoration works were made and the building was fixed as it had been precipitated and deviated from the vertical. Today, several shops are housed in Bezesteni, Thessaloniki.`,
