    "sourceTitle1": "White Tower Museum website",
    "description": `Since September 5, 2008, the White Tower Museum houses the new permanent exhibition of the history of Thessaloniki,  since it was founded in 316/15 BC. to our day. The exhibition presents briefly aspects of the history of the city, distinguished by its centuries-old, undisturbed historical presence. In its course in time Thessaloniki did not lose its "urban" and multicultural character. As he said, referring to the Thessalonians, Nikephoros Houmnos, politician who lived in the 13th and 14th century, and for some time he was the governor of Thessaloniki, "you have made it clear to everyone that no one lives without a homeland as long as Thessaloniki exists", describing in a document the tolerance of the Thessalonians towards the foreigners.
    </br></br>The exhibition was designed with respect to the architectural identity of the monument and its emergence. The large amount of information, which was to be presented in the small exhibition area of the monument (450 sq. M.), led to the solution of the use of multimedia (video, projections, interactive and audio applications) along with printed graphic compositions (photobanks) while the archaeological material to be used is minimal. The limited extent of space was also the reason why Greek is the only language of the exhibition. For the foreign visitors the solution of the audio guide in English was chosen.
    </br></br>The aim of the exhibition is, through the brief narrative of the history of Thessaloniki, to "recommend" the city mainly to its inhabitants and to stimulate their interest in further acquaintance through their thematic museums and monuments.
    </br></br>The exhibition is organized thematically. Each floor presents an issue that develops over time. A summary of the topic is made in the central area of the floor, while more detailed negotiation is taking place in the perimeter rooms.
    </br></br>Informative tables in the courtyard of the Tower give the first informations on the monument and the content of the exhibition.`,

